    "description": "We often talk about the class as a blueprint for an object. This is because classes define what properties and methods an object should have, in the form of a constructor. Consider this class representing a planet:\n​ Java Python public class Planet{ private double mass; public double getMass(){ return this.mass; } private double radius; public double getRadius(){ return this.radius; } public Planet(double mass, double radius){ this.mass = mass; this.radius = radius; } } class Planet @property def mass(self) -\u003e float: return self.__mass @property def radius(self) -\u003e float: return self.__radius def __init__(self, mass: float, radius: float) -\u003e None: self.__mass = mass self.__radius = radius It describes a planet as having a mass and a radius, which will be stored as the ratio of this planet’s attribute compared to Earth. We can create a specific planet by invoking its constructor, i.e.:",
